  "RM": {
    "name": "Risk Management",
    "summary": "Risk Management is worth roughly <strong>5 questions per 100-question Finance ICDC exam</strong> and on this cluster it's framed around <strong>financial and operational risk, internal/external controls, insurance, ethics, and enterprise risk management</strong>. The heaviest codes are <strong>RM:058 (internal vs. external risk control), RM:062 (enterprise risk management), RM:042 (technology to reduce risk), and RM:041/RM:043 (ethics & legal exposure)</strong>. Learn the risk-handling vocabulary and you'll bank these points.",
    "sections": [
      {
        "h": "RM:058 — Nature of risk control (internal vs. external)",
        "items": [
          "DECA's core distinction: <strong>internal risks</strong> come from <strong>inside</strong> the business and can be controlled (employee fraud, system failures, poor processes); <strong>external risks</strong> come from <strong>outside</strong> and largely can't be controlled (economy, competitors, natural disasters, regulation).",
          "DECA's tested finance example of an <strong>external risk: a change in the inflation rate</strong> — inflation is a macroeconomic force that devalues liquid assets and shifts consumer behavior, and the firm can't control it.",
          "Some external risks are <strong>uninsurable</strong> — broad market/economic risks (like a market-wide collapse or inflation) generally can't be covered by an insurance policy, unlike a fire or theft.",
          "Risk-control techniques DECA tests: installing <strong>automatic sprinklers</strong> = <strong>risk reduction</strong> (lowering the chance/severity of loss). Know the four responses: <strong>avoid, reduce/control, transfer (insure), and retain/assume</strong>.",
          "DECA tests this by giving a situation and asking 'internal or external?' or 'which risk-control technique is this?' — anchor on whether the source is inside or outside the firm's control."
        ]
      },
      {
        "h": "RM:062 — Enterprise risk management (ERM)",
        "items": [
          "<strong>ERM</strong> is an <strong>organization-wide strategy</strong> to identify, assess, and prepare for risks that could harm the firm's finances, operations, and objectives — it looks at risk holistically, not department by department.",
          "DECA tests the <strong>categories of risk</strong> ERM addresses. Example: a <strong>flood damaging a warehouse</strong> = <strong>operational risk</strong> (disruption to day-to-day operations/assets). Other categories: financial, strategic, compliance, and hazard risk.",
          "A <strong>disadvantage of ERM</strong> DECA points to: it can be <strong>costly, time-consuming, and complex</strong> to implement across an entire organization.",
          "ERM starts by <strong>identifying all risks</strong>, then <strong>prioritizing</strong> which are most critical — firms can't fix everything, so they rank by likelihood and impact.",
          "DECA tests this by naming a risk and asking which category it is, or asking for a benefit/drawback of ERM — know operational vs. financial vs. strategic."
        ]
      },
      {
        "h": "RM:042 — Technology to reduce risk",
        "items": [
          "DECA tests how firms use tech to <strong>protect financial data and systems</strong>.",
          "To protect <strong>digital financial data from fire, flood, and theft</strong>, the answer is <strong>data backups / cloud backups / off-site storage</strong> — a physical lock won't save data, but a backup will.",
          "To reduce the risk of <strong>network security breaches</strong>, businesses use <strong>firewalls, encryption, antivirus/anti-malware software, and access controls</strong>.",
          "<strong>Protective software</strong> minimizes losses from cyberattacks and data theft — increasingly critical as finance moves online.",
          "DECA tests this with 'what technology protects against X' — match the threat (data loss → backups; intruders → firewall/encryption)."
        ]
      },
      {
        "h": "RM:041 — Ethics in risk management",
        "items": [
          "DECA links <strong>ethics</strong> to risk: unethical behavior <strong>increases</strong> a firm's risk exposure (lawsuits, fines, lost trust).",
          "An <strong>ethical hazard / ethical issue</strong> example: <strong>deliberately concealing or misrepresenting financial information</strong> — this raises legal and reputational risk.",
          "Acting ethically (honesty, transparency, fair dealing) is itself a <strong>risk-reduction</strong> strategy because it prevents the costly fallout of scandals.",
          "DECA tests this by describing a questionable action and asking whether it's an ethical issue that raises risk — the dishonest/concealing option is the ethical hazard."
        ]
      },
      {
        "h": "RM:043 — Legal considerations affecting risk management",
        "items": [
          "DECA tests how firms limit <strong>legal liability</strong>.",
          "To reduce future legal problems, a company may require business partners to <strong>sign contracts/agreements</strong> that clearly define responsibilities — written terms transfer and clarify risk.",
          "<strong>Disclosure</strong> reduces legal risk: e.g., a pharmaceutical company <strong>listing the side effects</strong> of a medicine warns consumers and limits liability. Failing to disclose (concealing a client's true financial status) <strong>increases</strong> legal exposure.",
          "DECA tests this by asking how a firm protects itself legally — the answer involves clear contracts and full, honest disclosure."
        ]
      }
    ],
    "traps": "The #1 trap is mixing up <strong>internal vs. external risk</strong> — if the firm can't control it (inflation, market crash, weather), it's <strong>external</strong>, and broad economic risks are usually <strong>uninsurable</strong>. Second, students miscategorize ERM risks — a flooded warehouse is <strong>operational</strong>, not 'financial.' Third, on RM:042, a physical safeguard won't protect <strong>digital</strong> data — the answer is <strong>backups</strong>. Finally, remember the direction of ethics and disclosure: <strong>concealing information raises risk; disclosing and contracting lower it</strong> — don't pick the 'hide it' option."
  },
