    "summary": "<strong>Expect about 1 question</strong> on the Finance ICDC exam from Entrepreneurship. DECA tests the <strong>nature of entrepreneurship</strong> (what counts as an entrepreneurial venture), <strong>innovation</strong>, and <strong>business ethics for founders</strong>. Think of it as the mindset a person needs to start and run a finance-related business, such as a tax-prep firm, an independent financial-advisory practice, or a fintech startup.",
    "sections": [
      {
        "h": "Nature of entrepreneurship (EN:039)",
        "items": [
          "<strong>Entrepreneurship</strong> is the process of starting and running your own business while taking on the financial risk in hopes of profit. DECA tests this with founder scenarios — e.g., someone opening an independent <strong>financial-planning practice</strong> and deciding what services to offer.",
          "A first step before launching is identifying a <strong>product or service</strong> and a market need. The 2023 exam asks what an entrepreneur should do when they aren't sure what to sell yet — the answer is <strong>research opportunities and assess their own skills/interests</strong>, not jump straight to financing.",
          "Entrepreneurs accept <strong>uncertainty and personal financial risk</strong> (their own capital is on the line), which is the key difference from being an employee."
        ]
      },
      {
        "h": "Innovation vs. imitation (EN:039)",
        "items": [
          "An <strong>innovative</strong> endeavor creates or invents something new for the marketplace. The 2018 exam's correct answer was <strong>developing a brand-new device to sell</strong> — opening a coffee shop, buying a sushi <strong>franchise</strong>, or copying an existing model is imitation, not innovation.",
          "In finance, an innovative venture might be a new <strong>budgeting app</strong> or a novel <strong>payment platform</strong>; replicating an existing bank branch model is not innovative."
        ]
      },
      {
        "h": "Business ethics in entrepreneurship (EN:044)",
        "items": [
          "DECA tests this heavily: founders must be <strong>honest and transparent</strong> even when it costs them. The 2022 answer stressed being honest about the <strong>time commitment</strong> when hiring, because overburdened employees quit — short-term spin backfires.",
          "Ethical behavior builds <strong>long-term trust</strong> with employees, investors, and customers. For a finance startup, this means accurate disclosures and not overstating projected returns to attract <strong>investors or lenders</strong>."
        ]
      }
    ],
    "traps": "<strong>Innovation is not just 'a new business'</strong> — a franchise or another copycat shop is imitation, even if it's new to the owner. Also don't confuse the <strong>entrepreneur</strong> (owns the risk and the business) with a <strong>manager or employee</strong> (paid to run it). On ethics questions, the 'tempting shortcut' answer (sugarcoating, overpromising) is always wrong."
